  "prompt": "Is a passport compulsory to travel on flights within India?",
  "response": "No, a passport is **not** compulsory for traveling on domestic flights within India. While a passport is one of the accepted forms of identification, there are several other valid and widely accepted ID documents you can use to board a domestic flight. Here's a list of commonly accepted identification documents for domestic air travel in India:\n\n### **Accepted Forms of ID for Domestic Flights:**\n\n1. **Aadhaar Card**:\n   - A government-issued unique identification number.\n   \n2. **Voter ID Card (EPIC)**:\n   - Issued by the Election Commission of India.\n   \n3. **PAN Card (Permanent Account Number)**:\n   - Issued by the Income Tax Department.\n   \n4. **Driver\u2019s License**:\n   - Must be valid and issued by the Regional Transport Office (RTO).\n   \n5. **Government-Issued Photo ID Cards**:\n   - Includes IDs like those issued to government employees, students (such as IITians), etc.\n   \n6. **NREGA Job Card**:\n   - Issued under the National Rural Employment Guarantee Act.\n   \n7. **Ration Card with Photograph**:\n   - Must include a recent photograph of the holder.\n   \n8. **Student ID Cards**:\n   - Issued by recognized educational institutions.\n\n### **Key Points to Remember:**\n\n- **Validity**: Ensure that your chosen ID is valid and not expired.\n  \n- **Name Consistency**: The name on your ID should match the name on your flight ticket to avoid any discrepancies during check-in.\n  \n- **Original Document**: Carry the original document as photocopies or digital copies are generally not accepted.\n  \n- **Age Proof**: For certain categories like infants or children traveling without a parent, additional age proof might be required.\n\n### **Special Considerations:**\n\n- **E-Ticket and Boarding Pass**: While you can book tickets using a digital ID (like Aadhaar), you must present a physical copy of a valid ID at the airport.\n  \n- **International Residents**: If you are an international resident (e.g., OCI cardholder), carrying your passport might be necessary even for domestic flights, depending on airline policies.\n\n### **Conclusion:**\n\nWhile a passport is a universally accepted form of identification and can be used for domestic air travel in India, it is **not mandatory**. You have multiple alternatives to choose from based on what\u2019s convenient and accessible to you. Always ensure that whichever ID you choose is valid, carries your current photograph, and matches the name on your flight booking to ensure a smooth travel experience.",
